hat has increasingly sided with the vulnerable and oppressed. This book provides a concise history of progressively oriented Catholic Social Thought, which conveys the Catholic Church’s position on a variety of social justice concerns. Sharon Erickson Nepstad introduces key papal encyclicals and other church documents, showing how lay Catholics in the United States have put these ideas into practice through a creative and sometimes provocative political engagement. Nepstad also explores how these progressive movements have pressured the religious hierarchy to respond to pressing social issues, such as women’s ordination, conscription, and the morality of nuclear deterrence policies. Catholic Social Activism vividly depicts how these progressive movements have helped to shape the religious landscape of the United States, and how they have provoked controversy and debate among Catholics and non-Catholics alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCatholic Church-United States. 0aChristian sociologyxCatholic Church. 0aChristian sociology-Catholic Church. 0aChurch and social problemsxCatholic Church. 0aChurch and social problems-Catholic Church. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh  aCatholic Climate Change.  aCatholic Social Teachings.  aCatholic Social Thought.  aCatholic Worker.  aCatholic feminism.  aCentral America solidarity.  aCentral America.  aCésar Chávez.  aDolores Huerta.  aDorothy Day.  aEnvironmentalism.  aLaudato Si.  aMary Daly.  aNational Religious Partnership for the Environment.  aNew Sanctuary Movement.  aPacem in Terris.  aPax Christi.  aPledge of Resistance.  aPlowshares movement.  aPope Francis.  aPope John XXIII.  aPope Leo XIII.  aPope Pius XI.  aQuadragesimo Anno.  aRerum Novarum.  aRoman Catholic Womenpriests.  aRosemary Radfo